<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAUDIS SECRET STAKE IN MARINA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although Saudis secretly obtaining large interests in Marina leases with the 
blind approval of the Board of Supervisors offends me, it most certainly does 
not surprise me. With possibly one exception, this board almost invariably 
represents interests of big money -- not the electorate. 
</P>
<P>
It angers me that the citizens of the county continue to tolerate the board's 
cozy relationship with land developers (desecraters is a more descriptive term) 
merely because they, and other fat-cat moneyed interests contribute much more 
to campaign funds than can the average voter. 
</P>
<P>
It is high time the voters of Los Angeles County demand a return in the 
governance of the county. Such reform should begin with increasing board 
membership to at least nine members. Such a size increase would insure more 
equitable representation. 
</P>
<P>
A second step should be a separation of powers. Five men should not have total 
control over all county functions and decisions. At the very least, legislative 
and executive powers should be separate. Some authority, directly responsible 
to the people, i.e., elected, should have veto powers over the continuing 
exploitation of this county's land and people by five, money-hungry 
politicians. 
</P>
<P>
MARCELLA S. McGLOTHLIN 
</P>
<P>
Malibu 
</P>
</TEXT>
