<HEADLINE>
<P>
EX-LEADERS BUILT LUXURY VILLAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
EAST BERLIN 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Now-disgraced East German leaders built luxury villas of Canadian pine with 
Italian mosaic floors and expensive West German bathroom fittings, the East 
German Berliner Zeitung said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
Under the headline, "Secret Dwellings Behind Thick Hedges," the newspaper 
quoted a former member of the special state company that built the houses as 
saying he understood the villas were for the children, fathers, uncles and 
grandfathers of prominent East German politicians. 
</P>
<P>
The paper said former Economics Minister Guenther Mittag had one of the villas 
and another belonged to the now-dismissed president of the East German 
Parliament, Horst Sindemann. 
</P>
<P>
The paper said it is giving all the material it had researched for the article 
to a special parliamentary commission charged with investigating corruption 
among the fallen East German politicians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
EAST GERMANY -- GOVERNMENT OFFICIALS; LIFESTYLES; HOUSING -- EAST GERMANY; 
POLITICAL CORRUPTION 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
