<HEADLINE>
<P>
VAN TO VAN COMBAT; 
</P>
<P>
IT'S CHAOS, SOMETIMES, AT LAX AS MORE THAN 30 FIRMS VIE FOR PASSENGERS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JUBE SHIVER Jr., TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It was smooth going in front of the Los Angeles International Airport one 
recent Wednesday as two Department of Airport officers policed the movement of 
airport shuttle vans in and out of Terminal 1. But once the officers left, the 
usual chaos resumed. 
</P>
<P>
Within minutes, 12 airport shuttle vans from five different companies descended 
on the passenger island. About half of the drivers jumped out and began trying 
to solicit passengers to share a $10 van ride downtown or pay up to $50 each to 
go to such faraway destinations as Newport Beach. Inevitably, arguments broke 
out as fully loaded vans pinned to the curb battled empty vans still seeking 
passengers. 
</P>
<P>
"It's pure hell out there," said John Taylor, who has been driving vans for 
Supershuttle since 1986. "If you are not fighting other vans, you are fighting 
the (rental car) buses, the hotel buses and passenger cars." 
</P>
<P>
With thousands of passengers arriving each hour at Los Angeles International 
Airport and the relatively low cost of acquiring a vehicle, van shuttles may 
look like an easy, no-risk business. But the proliferating number of airport 
shuttle van companies has produced cutthroat competition, airport congestion 
and almost daily confrontations between drivers at the world's third-busiest 
airport, officials say. 
</P>
<P>
Some 30 privately operated van companies with 650 vehicles now serve the 
airport, compared to just two companies in 1971, according to airport 
officials. Competition has increased so much that Airlink, a Southern 
California commercial bus operator, cited the skyrocketing growth of vans when 
it shut down its 19-mile-long airport-to-downtown bus service last year. 
</P>
<P>
Even industry leader Supershuttle, with about 200 vans and estimated annual 
revenue last year of nearly $50 million, is feeling the pinch. Last year, it 
took out a $14,000 newspaper advertisement to tell Department of Airport 
officials that Supershuttle and its customers had " . . . the most to lose from 
chaos and irresponsible practices at the airport." 
</P>
<P>
"We are all having problems with the number of shuttle van companies serving 
the airport," said Rod Ramsey, chairman of the Shuttle Van Assn. of Southern 
California and president of City Shuttle in Van Nuys. "We are a young industry, 
and the potential for growth is tremendous. (But) we have a few bad apples we 
need to weed out." 
</P>
<P>
In response to the complaints, the Department of Airports imposed a moratorium 
in September on new van operators and is considering new rules that would limit 
the time that drivers could solicit passengers during each stop and even force 
van operators to install devices that would electronically track how many trips 
the vans made to and from the airport. 
</P>
<P>
"There's too much wheeling and dealing going on on the curbs," said Tom 
Drischler, transportation coordinator for the Department of Airports' unit that 
oversees ground transportation. "Drivers spend more time on the ground hustling 
up business than they do driving their vans." 
</P>
<P>
Almost unheard of a decade ago, shuttle vans now carry tens of thousands of 
passengers who used to drive to the airport or relied on taxis and buses to 
transport them. Profit margins for operators are razor thin, typically less 
than 2%, several shuttle van companies say. But transportation experts say vans 
have become popular because they offer a compromise between a taxi, which is 
faster but costs more, and a bus, which is less expensive but slower. 
</P>
<P>
On the airport-to-downtown route abandoned by Airlink, for example, cab fare is 
a flat $26.50 and van service is $9 to $11, compared to the $6.50 that Airlink 
had charged last year. 
</P>
<P>
"Basically, you have got economics accounting for the growing popularity of 
vans," said Martin Markovich, transportation planner for the Southern 
California Assn. of Governments. "But you also have demographic changes as 
well." 
</P>
<P>
Markovich noted that there is a greater percentage of single households or 
dual-income families in which husband and wife hold jobs and, therefore, don't 
have time to transport household members or guests to and from the airport. 
</P>
<P>
"Another demographic change," Markovich said, "is that most people don't go 
downtown anymore." With urban sprawl, he said, more passengers arriving at LAX 
are going to a wider variety of destinations -- stretching from Orange County 
to the San Fernando Valley. As a result, he said, large commercial carriers 
such as Airlink have trouble filling up a 50-passenger bus that goes to a 
single destination. 
</P>
<P>
By contrast, vans operate in a much more flexible manner: They pick up 
passengers by appointment at their homes or businesses (very much as taxis do), 
but unlike taxis, vans may make one or more stops to pick up additional 
passengers along the way. Travelers can hail vans, just as they do taxis, at 
designated points outside airline terminals. 
</P>
<P>
It is this last aspect of van service, however, that has made van competition 
especially fierce in California, experts say. 
</P>
<P>
In many states, door-to-door airport vans may only pick up passengers who have 
arranged for the service in advance -- normally by at least a day. But 
California regulators operate under "a very loose interpretation" of what 
constitutes advance notice, said Ray A. Mundy, a transportation professor at 
the University of Tennessee who is executive director of the Airport Ground 
Transportation Assn. 
</P>
<P>
If a customer calls from the airport or hails a van from the curb in 
California, that constitutes advance notice, Mundy said. 
</P>
<P>
But while the short-notice rule can be convenient for those seeking 
transportation on the spur of the moment, it can be frustrating for passengers 
who want to be delivered to their destination in a timely fashion. 
</P>
<P>
Craig Stack, a customer service representative supervisor for Los Angeles-based 
TTMC Co., which helps manage van shuttle passenger relations, tells of 
passengers who have been driven around the airport for 20 minutes or longer 
while the driver seeks more customers to fill up his van. 
</P>
<P>
And the Department of Airport's Drischler said his unit recently discovered 
that some van drivers were trading away passengers like chattel to other fully 
loaded vans headed for the same destination because the drivers didn't deem it 
financially worthwhile to make a trip with fewer than three customers. 
</P>
<P>
"The only way we found out about it was that one of the passengers left his 
luggage in the van he was forced out of," Drischler said. 
</P>
<P>
Surprisingly, such incidents have generated few complaints to regulatory 
authorities, said Ebi Esule, a transportation engineer with the state Public 
Utilities Commission, which regulates van and bus service within California. 
</P>
<P>
"My impression is that the public feels they (vans) fill a very vital public 
need," said Esule. 
</P>
<P>
The van explosion began in 1981, when the PUC opened up a market then dominated 
by cabs and buses. According to a Department of Airports' study completed two 
years ago, vans shuttled less than 3% of airport passengers, versus 54% using 
private cars and 16% using taxis. (Buses, rental cars and other forms of 
transportation also had slices of the market.) 
</P>
<P>
Today, however, most observers believe that vans have increased their share of 
the estimated 44 million travelers who use LAX each year. 
</P>
<P>
They have been aided in their expansion by the PUC. 
</P>
<P>
Before 1981, the PUC granted few licenses to new airport bus or van companies. 
"If there was a bus line that already served the area, the commission would say 
no," said PUC spokeswoman Carole Kretzer. 
</P>
<P>
But the commission changed its philosophy as federal officials continued 
deregulating transportation among the states in the early 1980s. The watershed 
year, experts say, came in 1981 when the commission allowed the Trailways Bus 
Co. to operate along Greyhound routes. 
</P>
<P>
"Now it's very open," said Kretzer. "We encourage more competition because, 
theoretically, it leads to better service and lower prices." 
</P>
<P>
Van companies now serve virtually every neighborhood in Southern California. 
One company -- Seoul Shuttle -- specializes in serving Koreatown. Passenger 
rates have barely risen among shuttle operators in the past five years, experts 
say. 
</P>
<P>
But the free granting of licenses to new van operators has upset Department of 
Airport officials and industry leaders, who banded together earlier this year 
and formed the shuttle van association to help lobby for stricter van operating 
rules. 
</P>
<P>
"If they throw this thing open to anyone," groused Mitchell Rouse, president of 
Supershuttle, "they are going to get the lowest common denominator of van 
operator, who doesn't have the burden of having to provide a system to get 
customers to the airport . . . (but) only flags them down at the curb in front 
of the terminals." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, 'We are all having problems with the number of shuttle van companies. . 
. . We are a young industry, and the potential for growth is tremendous. (But) 
we have a few bad apples we need to weed out.' -- ROD RAMSEY, Shuttle Van Assn. 
of Southern California ; Photo, vans GEORGE R. FRY / Los Angeles Times; 
Drawing, vans, Horacio Fidel Cardo / for The Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
