<HEADLINE>
<P>
FYI, CHARACTER ON 'MURPHY BROWN' IS NO TED BAXTER CLONE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN N. GOUDAS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Murphy Brown" has been compared to the old and great "Mary Tyler Moore Show" 
by the critics and viewers. Some have taken the comparison further, comparing 
Joe Regalbuto's character of Frank to Gavin MacLeod's Murray and labeling 
Charles Kimbrough's Jim Dial as the series Ted Baxter, which was played by Ted 
Knight. 
</P>
<P>
If you want to see Charles Kimbrough get a rise, make this comparison to his 
face. He is thoroughly justified in his annoyance. Ted Baxter was a buffoon, 
even as brilliantly played as he was by Ted Knight. 
</P>
<P>
Jim Dial, on the other hand, is a veteran newsman and anchor on "FYI" who has 
probably worked with some of the heavyweights in the field. In fact tonight's 
episode (which airs at 9 p.m. on CBS and guest stars Walter Cronkite) shows 
Dial being roasted for his 25 years with the network. 
</P>
<P>
Kimbrough's own description of his character is probably the best and the most 
accurate. 
</P>
<P>
"Jim Dial is full of surprises. He is a professional who does the job and does 
it fully. Mythically speaking, Jim sees himself as a laconic Hemingway hero. 
He's buttoned up but highly emotional inside. He thinks he is secure in his 
armor-clad business suit, but he's wary of those closing in on him. He has an 
actor's vanity." 
</P>
<P>
Kimbrough admitted "Murphy Brown" came into his life at a time when he needed 
it most. Not that he wasn't working. In fact, he was working all the time but 
mostly on the Broadway stage. Gradually, he found that he was playing 
variations on the same role. "Luckily for me 'Murphy Brown' came my way and I 
thought this might do it." 
</P>
<P>
Kimbrough recalls the night the cast gathered at exec-producer/creator Diane 
English's house to read the script. The chemistry was there right from the 
start. 
</P>
<P>
"I knew at that point we had a chance of making it work. Candice was the big 
surprise. The critics fell all over themselves with praise. Candice thirsted 
for comedy. She craved to play a character who was funny and this was her first 
big opportunity." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Charles Kimbrough is newsman Jim Dial on 'Murphy Brown'. Associated 
Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
